    "body": "@jborean93 Hi. The Principle of Least Astonishment is predicated on the fact that if you try hard enough, you can find some justification for everything after the fact.\r\n\r\nThe cmdlet's current behavior impedes the natural workflow of a system administrator because of its perverse (and definitely unintended) use of wildcards. To wit, wildcards are supposed to help select multiple files or folders, not make selecting one harder. This behavior, even if well-documented, does not lead to predictable script outcome. Rather, it acts as a form of a minefield that triggers instant-deathâ€“style failure modes to scripts when the user least expects it.",
